CB,<br><br>
I'll post the general list for PTSD upstairs in a few days, along with some links. I have a lot of information on my 'Nam page at:<br><br>
http://www.netcom.com/~art16/NamVet.html<br><br>
Poke around there and you might find what you are looking for, too.<br><br>
I have a theory about 'Nam Vets and the VFW based upon my own feelings. When I returned home from 'Nam, I actually concealed my Vietnam Veteran status, tried to deny it, never talked about it, and really wanted to get as far away as possible from anything military or government connected. The VFW was the LAST place I wanted to go. I had also heard stories that some 'Nam Vets were not greeted with respect and civility at the VFW, and were in fact individually blamed for &quot;loosing the war&quot;, a circumstance over which the NamVet had absolutely no control. Shame, fear, guilt, and unresolved conflicts piled up into a mental paralysis and depression.<br><br>
My decorations finally went up on the wall nine months or so ago. It took me three months of carrrying them in and out of the office before I finally took the plunge. I was actually scared to death, and was reliving some pretty ugly moments whenever I thought of hanging them up. I am over pretty much now, though there are still twinges once in a while, and I am now beginning to look upon them with pride. My father-in-law pays for my VFW membership. He started that when my head came unglued with this stuff two years ago. He is a WW2 Vet. I feel progress is afoot!<br><br>
From my own feelings again, NamVets formed their own organization because of the mistrust of anyone who was not a NamVet. I feel this very strongly still, and I have difficulty in discussing some things with others in whom I do not have complete trust. Trust is an important issue with me, though my participation here on this site, combined with a lot of hard work elsewhere, has eased this somewhat. Vulnerability must be balanced with complete trust in the minds of some in order for them to resolve the very bad issues.<br><br>
I am beginning to discover trust in myself with NamVet issues. That is why I can openly discuss some NamVet things here and can handle what is thrown at me.<br><br>
It is no wonder that some of us actually built bunkers in our cellars and lived in them. I, fortunately, was not that severe, but I had my places. Some of the guys I know still use their bunkers.<br><br>
I am digressing a little, but I think I have painted a fairly realistic picture of the alternative and isolationist reality into which some of our brothers retreated. That's why VFW avoidance was an issue, among may others.<br><br>
Art
